Part 5

The staff room of the Bagbazar shelter had seven plastic chairs and one long wooden bench where the junior volunteers sat. 

Vikram stood near the glass window. The neem trees outside in the courtyard were losing their leaves, the dry yellow blades falling silently onto the grey stone floor.

"I am going," Vikram said, looking out at the yard.

Sarita looked up from the table. She was holding a glass of red tea, her hands trembling slightly against the warm glass. "Where?" she asked.

"Nowhere," Vikram said. "Just out."

"But the shelter, Vikram," one of the senior patients, an old tailor named Ghosh, said from his chair. "The Barasat license is still pending with the health department. The distributors won't talk to us if you're not here to sign."

"They will talk to Sarita," Vikram said, turning his head. "She has the register."

"We need you, Baba," Ananya said from the corner of the wooden bench. 

She was eighteen now, her face mature. She was still holding the ledger with the green cloth cover, her fingers tracing the worn seam of the spine.

"The children at the school ask when you are coming to tell the crow story," she said. "They have been waiting in the yard since Tuesday."

"Tell them the crow flew away," Vikram said. He looked at her, his face quiet. "I want to be a free bird, Ananya."

"Even a bird has a nest, Vikram," Sarita said, her voice dropping.

"Only when it is tired," Vikram said.

He picked up his small leather bag. He had left his second shirt on the bench, carrying only the clothes he wore—a faded cotton kurta and the rubber slippers he had bought at the Shobhabazar market. 

He walked out. He didn't use the main wooden door; he walked through the side corridor, passed the kitchen where the red tea was still simmering on the coal stove, and went out into the lane.

---

For three years, he lived on the streets of Bagbazar. 

He slept on the concrete verandah of the Ramkrishna Mission, his head resting on his rolled-up canvas bag. The monks knew him as the quiet old man who swept the temple steps before the morning prayers began.

They offered him a plate of dal and rice in the noon. He ate what they gave, washed his steel plate at the tap, and sat near the river bank for the rest of the day, watching the boats.

The children near the local school started calling him Budha Baba. It wasn't because he was truly old, but because he had the time to sit on the concrete drain edge and listen to their stories about the street dogs and the broken kites.

He didn't carry a phone. If the shelter needed him, Ramu's nephew would walk down to the river bank and tell him. But they rarely called; they had learned to run the shelter's math themselves.

---

The call came on a rainy Tuesday morning in July 2018. 

Vikram was sleeping on the verandah of the Mission, the wind from the Hooghly river spraying light drops of rain over his bare feet. Ramu's nephew came running through the mud, his shirt soaked, holding a plastic pouch containing Vikram's old Nokia phone.

"Baba," the boy said, out of breath. "Ananya called from the shelter. It is urgent."

Vikram took the phone out of the plastic. The screen was scratched, and the battery showed only one bar of green light. "Ananya?"

"Baba," her voice was fast, tight with the specific panic of the emergency ward. "It's Kavita. The girl from the Barasat branch. She got her medical report yesterday. She is standing at the bypass bridge. She wants to jump."

"I am coming," Vikram said.

He didn't take his bag. He left it on the Mission verandah, near the sweeper's broom.

He ran. His rubber slippers were thin, the soles sliding on the wet mud of the Bagbazar lanes. The bypass bridge was two kilometers away.

When he reached the bridge, Kavita was standing on the concrete ledge of the railing. Her hands were holding the cold iron pipe, and she was looking down at the railway tracks below.

The rain was heavier now, the water running fast along the concrete. A crowd of truck drivers had gathered at a distance, shouting, but nobody had gone close to her.

Vikram walked onto the bridge, his steps unhurried. He didn't shout. He didn't tell her that life was beautiful or that things would get better.

He simply stood beside her on the concrete ledge, his faded kurta soaked through by the rain, his feet cold in his slippers.

"The water down there is very dirty," Vikram said, looking at the tracks.

Kavita turned her head slowly, her face white, her eyes wet with the rain. "I have the bad blood, Baba," she whispered.

"I know," Vikram said. "Ananya had it too. She is still writing the ledger at the desk. Come. Ramu's nephew has the tea ready. It is cheap tea, but it is hot."

She looked at his hand. His hand was rough, the calluses yellow and hard from years of well rope, the nails grey with river sand.

"Come," he said again.

She looked at the tracks below, then she stepped down from the ledge. She didn't cry; she simply took his hand, her fingers cold and trembling against his calluses.

Vikram led her down the ramp to the police ambulance. A local MLA, who had arrived in a white Ambassador car with a red light on the top, stepped out of the vehicle. 

He recognized Vikram from the old Kolkata press meets. "Ahuja saab," the MLA said, holding an umbrella over Vikram's head. "Get in. The car will drop you back to the hospital."

Vikram pushed the umbrella aside. "The car is too clean," Vikram said. "It will get wet."

He walked away. He crossed the bypass road, his slippers sliding on the mud. 

The rain had stopped for a moment, the sun coming through the grey clouds and turning the wet road into a line of shining silver.

Behind him, a crowd had gathered near the bridge. A local strike was happening, and the workers were shouting slogans, throwing stones at the passing auto rickshaws.

A motorcycle came fast from the wrong side of the divider, its headlight off, its engine roaring over the shouts of the crowd.

Vikram didn't hear the horn. He was looking at the well tap of the shelter visible between the buildings, thinking of the hot red tea that would be waiting for him.

There was a sharp, dry sound of brakes, and then the impact. 

He felt the road rising to meet his shoulder. He felt his rubber slipper flying off his foot into the air. 

And then the darkness came, quiet and cold, like the shadow of the neem trees in the Bagbazar courtyard.

---

*"Please... side... please... give a little side..."*

The voice wasn't loud. Yet it cut through the noise of the casualty corridor. 

An old man was lying on a stretcher, his white cotton shirt brown near the shoulder, one rubber slipper still remaining on his right foot. 

The NGO girl was walking beside him, her left elbow bleeding, her sleeve torn. She bent down, removed the remaining slipper, and placed both carefully under the stretcher.

"It doesn't look nice," she said, her fingers dusty. "Wearing only one slipper."

